A RESOLUTION
1 Creating the House Study Committee on Protecting Working Families; and for other
2 purposes.
3 WHEREAS, the State of Georgia receives approximately $19 billion from the federal
4 government and any federal budget cuts will require the General Assembly to significantly
5 slash funding, which will negatively affect Georgians' salaries, quality of life, access to
6 healthcare, and ability to access essential services; and
7 WHEREAS, reductions in federal Medicaid and Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program
8 (SNAP) funding will have a significant negative impact on certain vulnerable populations,
9 small businesses, rural communities, veterans, and first responders in this state; and
10 WHEREAS, according to the Georgia Department of Public Health, nearly 2.5 million
11 Georgians rely on Medicaid, including low-income working families, children, seniors, and
12 people with disabilities, and any reduction in federal Medicaid funding could lead to higher
13 uninsured rates, more expensive health insurance plans for families and employers, and an
14 increased financial strain on hospitals, particularly in rural areas; and
15 WHEREAS, over 1.4 million Georgians depend on SNAP benefits to afford basic nutrition,
16 with working families, single parents, and low-income seniors being among the largest
