17 recipients, and reductions in SNAP funding could result in higher food insecurity rates,
18 increased pressure on food banks, and negative health outcomes for vulnerable populations;
19 and
20 WHEREAS, food insecurity remains a pressing issue in Georgia, with 13.1 percent of
21 residents (approximately 1 in 8) experiencing food insecurity, including 18.4 percent of
22 children (approximately 1 in 5), and the demand for food assistance has surged due to rising
23 grocery prices and economic challenges; and
24 WHEREAS, working families in Georgia already face rising healthcare costs, limited access
25 to health insurance, and disparities in maternal health outcomes, disproportionately affecting
26 women, children, and communities of color; and
27 WHEREAS, Georgia has one of the highest uninsured rates in the country (13.4 percent), and
28 cuts to Medicaid funding could further erode access to affordable healthcare for working
29 families and small business employees; and
30 WHEREAS, Georgia ranks among the worst states for maternal mortality, with Black
31 mothers facing a mortality rate more than twice that of white mothers, and expanded
32 Medicaid access has been shown to improve maternal health outcomes; and
33 WHEREAS, over 152,000 women in Georgia live in maternity care deserts, putting them at
34 greater risk of adverse health outcomes due to lack of accessible and equitable maternal care;
35 and
36 WHEREAS, the loss of SNAP and Medicaid benefits would have cascading economic
37 effects, including reduced consumer spending, financial strain on small businesses and the
38 state, and increased uncompensated care costs for hospitals and healthcare providers; and
