39 WHEREAS, strengthening state based protections, such as emergency Medicaid funds, food
40 security programs, and small business tax incentives, can help mitigate the negative impacts
41 of federal policy changes and ensure that working families, first responders, veterans, and
42 vulnerable populations continue to have access to essential healthcare and nutrition; and
43 WHEREAS, the Georgia legislature understands that certain state-driven protections may be
44 necessary to ensure that these individuals, businesses, and communities continue to have
45 access to essential healthcare and food security benefits, including, but not limited to, the
46 following protections:
47 (1) State emergency Medicaid fund. The fund would provide healthcare coverage to
48 individuals who lose Medicaid benefits due to federal policy changes;
49 (2) State food security fund. The fund would provide grocery assistance benefits to
50 first responders, veterans, and other eligible individuals equivalent to any loss of SNAP
51 benefits due to federal policy changes;
52 (3) Small business tax credits. Small business employers would receive tax credits for
53 making certain healthcare contributions related to responding to reductions in Medicaid
54 funding;
55 (4) Affordable insurance pool for small businesses. Individuals affected by reductions
56 in Medicaid funding would have the option to participate in and have access to subsidized
57 healthcare coverage;
58 (5) State funded food purchase program. The state would purchase and distribute
59 local produce, dairy, and meat to food banks, K-12 schools, senior meal programs, and
60 families with an incarcerated parent or a parent recently released from incarceration;
61 (6) State funded Medicaid buy-in program. Individuals who lose Medicaid benefits
62 due to federal policy changes would be permitted to purchase state sponsored coverage
63 at subsidized rates;
64 (7) State funded maternity care grants. Pregnant women from low-income
65 households, children in households that lose access to benefits under Medicaid or the
