66 Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), and low-income mothers denied abortion
67 access due to state restrictions would receive direct financial assistance from the state for
68 maternity healthcare expenses; and
69 (8) State funded grants to food assistance organizations. Church-run pantries and
70 religious, nonprofit organizations would receive state dollar-for-dollar matching grants
71 to support their existing efforts of providing food assistance; and
72 WHEREAS, a study is needed to evaluate these protections and others, determine policy
73 goals, and identify appropriate legislative actions to mitigate any adverse impact of federal
74 Medicaid and SNAP funding changes on these individuals, businesses, and communities.
75 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
76 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
77 on Protecting Working Families.
78 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of 11 members of the
79 House of Representatives to be appointed by the Speaker of the House of
80 Representatives. The Speaker shall designate a member of the committee as chairperson
81 of the committee.
82 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
83 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
84 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate.
85 (4) Meetings. The chairperson shall call all meetings of the committee. The committee
86 may conduct such meetings at such places and at such times as it may deem necessary or
87 convenient to enable it to exercise fully and effectively its powers, perform its duties, and
88 accomplish the objectives and purposes of this resolution.
89 (5) Allowances and funding. The legislative members of the committee shall receive
90 the allowances provided for in Code Section 28-1-8 of the Official Code of Georgia
91 Annotated. The allowances authorized by this resolution shall not be received by any
